    {
      "doi": "10.1093/hgs/dcag042",
      "title": "Journeys of visual knowledge: images from concentration camp inmates before and after the liberation",
      "authors": "Falldorf, Ella",
      "journal_name": "Holocaust and Genocide Studies",
      "journal_abbrev": "Holo Geno Stud",
      "issn": "8756-6583",
      "volume": null,
      "issue": null,
      "pages": null,
      "abstract": "Abstract Prior to the Allies’ photo campaigns at the war's end, inmates had already recognized the need to visually document what happened in the Nazi concentration camps. The Jewish artist Walter Spitzer recalled his instructions from a member of the resistance organization in Buchenwald: “We want you to observe what happens here, look everywhere, remember what you see, and draw! You are our camera!” Since their creation, his and others’ drawings have been compared to photography. This article analyzes what such a comparison entails and traces the production, content, and reception of images recorded in the camps. It then examines the changes these images, and the artists’ interpretations of Buchenwald, underwent when they moved from the camp to other places after the liberation. Spitzer and others belonged to a resistance network in Buchenwald that produced and circulated visual knowledge. Upon their release from the camp, former inmates edited their drawings before disseminating their visual knowledge. Creating this imagery was a collaborative effort both during and after the war, when former camp inmates migrated all over Europe. This article follows the different elements and transnational collaborations that influenced the creation of a new imagery framed by camp experiences, cultural traditions, political opinions, and the shifting social and historical environment.",
      "url": "https://doi.org/10.1093/hgs/dcag042",
      "published_online": "2026-06-19T00:00:00",
      "published_print": null,
      "published_date": "2026-06-19T00:00:00",
      "subjects": null,
      "article_type": "journal-article"
    },
    {
      "doi": "10.1093/hgs/dcag043",
      "title": "The Bund and the media: how knowledge of the Holocaust spread in the labor movement, the Mexican press, and beyond",
      "authors": "Gleason Freidberg, Tamara",
      "journal_name": "Holocaust and Genocide Studies",
      "journal_abbrev": "Holo Geno Stud",
      "issn": "8756-6583",
      "volume": null,
      "issue": null,
      "pages": null,
      "abstract": "Abstract This article examines Bundists’ efforts from June to December 1942 to disseminate news in Mexico about the Holocaust. These months were a critical period when detailed reports about the systematic extermination of Jews reached the Allies through various channels. In Mexico, as in the United States and England, the Bundists were among the first to spread the news about the Nazi genocide. These Yiddish-speaking antifascists talked about the mass killings in political forums, mobilized the Mexican labor movement in protest of the genocide, and published articles in the Mexican press emphasizing the Jewish identity of most of the Nazi victims. Their transnational connections with the Jewish labor movement were instrumental in garnering the support of local antifascist groups. By analyzing the efforts of this overlooked group in Latin America, this article provides new insights into Yiddish-speaking antifascist transnational networks during the Holocaust. Additionally, this article contributes to recent literature on the role of antifascist immigrants and exiles within the Mexican left, as this literature has mainly focused on German-speaking antifascists. By emphasizing the importance of multilingualism among Yiddish- and Spanish-speaking activists in Mexico, this work challenges the idea that Jews had to choose between belonging to a minority community or working as part of non-Jewish antifascist groups.",
      "url": "https://doi.org/10.1093/hgs/dcag043",
      "published_online": "2026-06-25T00:00:00",
      "published_print": null,
      "published_date": "2026-06-25T00:00:00",
      "subjects": null,
      "article_type": "journal-article"
    },
